column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Cattle numbers were back this week with 613 head penned, made up of 368 young cattle, 219 cows, 22 grown bulls and a few pens of open auction young cattle. The quality was mixed with cows making up a third of the offering. Most of the regular buying group attended and operated in a market similar to last week. A few cents dearer on medium weight grown steers, to 10c/kg easier on heavy grown heifers, 10c to 20c/kg easier on yearling trade heifers and similar on the cows. Bulls sold 8c to 10c/kg dearer. 

Young cattle sold to the trade from 236 to 380c and feeders paid from 232c to 380c/kg. Plainer types sold from 180c to 190c/kg. 

Medium grown steers sold from 348c to 410c, with heavier weights selling from 303 to 374c/kg. Feeders paid from 266c to 380c/kg. Heavy weight heifers sold from 320c to 380c with feeders and restockers paying from 272c to 364c/kg. 

Medium weight cows sold from 180c to 210c. Heavy 3 and 4 score cows sold from 300c to 335c, with the plainer types selling from 265c to 288c/kg. Feeders paid 180c/kg for cows. Bulls sold from 200c to 320c, feeders paid from 210c to 310c/kg for young bulls. 


Market Reporter - Graham Pymer.
